docs.abstract: House Democrats closed in on a compromise with the Trump administration that would provide paid sick leave and free testing as coronavirus fears fueled a steep sell-off in stocks.
docs.snippet: House Democrats closed in on a compromise with the Trump administration that would provide paid sick leave and free testing as coronavirus fears fueled a steep sell-off in stocks.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Financial markets plunged on Thursday in the biggest one-day drop since the Black Monday stock market crash of 1987, and Congress neared a deal with the White House on a sweeping economic rescue package to respond to the colossal effect of the coronavirus pandemic.

headline.main: Congress Nears Stimulus Deal With White House as Wall Street Suffers Rout
headline.print_headline: Worst Rout for Wall Street Since 1987 Crash

byline.original: By Emily Cochrane, Jeanna Smialek and Jim Tankersley

docs.abstract: The Treasury secretary has emerged as President Trump’s bridge across the aisle.
docs.snippet: The Treasury secretary has emerged as President Trump’s bridge across the aisle.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When America’s financial system teetered on the brink in September 2008, the Treasury secretary, Henry M. Paulson Jr., knelt down in the White House’s Roosevelt Room and pleaded with Speaker Nancy Pelosi not to withdraw her support for a $700 billion bailout package that was intended to fend off an economic collapse.

headline.main: With Echoes of 2008, Mnuchin and Pelosi Hammer Out a Rescue Deal
headline.print_headline: This Time, It’s Mnuchin Joining Pelosi in Coming to the Rescue

docs.abstract: The Department of Health and Human Services and the Food and Drug Administration are funding private companies that are rushing faster tests to the market.
docs.snippet: The Department of Health and Human Services and the Food and Drug Administration are funding private companies that are rushing faster tests to the market.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration, facing fierce criticism over a failure to test broadly for the coronavirus, said on Friday that it would set up drive-through testing, start a website to help Americans find a test, and set up new private partnerships to speed tests to the market.

headline.main: Trump Administration Moves to Speed Coronavirus Testing
headline.print_headline: As Pressure Builds, the Trump Administration Moves to Speed Up Testing

docs.abstract: The Trump administration says Americans returning from coronavirus hot spots are being screened for symptoms. Some travelers say that is not happening.
docs.snippet: The Trump administration says Americans returning from coronavirus hot spots are being screened for symptoms. Some travelers say that is not happening.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As thousands of Americans flee from Europe and other centers of the coronavirus outbreak, many travelers are reporting no health screenings upon departure and few impediments at U.S. airports beyond a welcome home greeting.

headline.main: Travelers From Coronavirus Hot Spots Say They Faced No Screening

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — There was one big question looming on Friday over the Rose Garden, where President Trump held an afternoon news conference and announced new emergency measures to combat the spread of the coronavirus.

docs.abstract: President Trump issued national guidelines that included closing schools and avoiding bars, restaurants and groups of more than 10 as he prepared for months of upheaval.
docs.snippet: President Trump issued national guidelines that included closing schools and avoiding bars, restaurants and groups of more than 10 as he prepared for months of upheaval.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump, under pressure to take more significant steps to slow the spreading coronavirus, recommended on Monday that Americans stop unnecessary travel and avoid bars, restaurants and groups of more than 10 people, as he warned that the outbreak could extend well into the summer.

headline.main: Trump Urges Limits Amid Pandemic, but Stops Short of National Mandates
headline.print_headline: Trump Urges Limits as Virus Batters Economy

docs.abstract: The companies funded Russia’s social media-fueled interference in the 2016 election, prosecutors said. But they tried to weaponize the case instead of fight it.
docs.snippet: The companies funded Russia’s social media-fueled interference in the 2016 election, prosecutors said. But they tried to weaponize the case instead of fight it.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Justice Department moved on Monday to drop charges against two Russian shell companies accused of financing schemes to interfere in the 2016 election, saying that they were exploiting the case to gain access to delicate information that Russia could weaponize.

headline.main: Justice Dept. Moves to Drop Charges Against Russian Firms Filed by Mueller
headline.print_headline: Charges Filed by Mueller Against Russian Companies May Be Dropped

docs.abstract: A new study questions the court’s practice of automatically granting argument time to the solicitor general as a “friend of the court.”
docs.snippet: A new study questions the court’s practice of automatically granting argument time to the solicitor general as a “friend of the court.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — There were more than 70 friend-of-the-court briefs filed in the big abortion case argued last week at the Supreme Court. But only one such friend was granted time to argue alongside the parties: the Office of the Solicitor General, the elite unit of the Justice Department that represents the federal government in the court.

headline.main: The Supreme Court Has a Special ‘Friend’: The Justice Department
headline.print_headline: Justices Greet Old ‘Friend’ at the Bar

docs.abstract: The central bank urged banks to work with their affected customers and moved to keep the financial system functioning smoothly.
docs.snippet: The central bank urged banks to work with their affected customers and moved to keep the financial system functioning smoothly.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Federal Reserve tried to insulate both Main Street and Wall Street from the coronavirus’s economic fallout on Monday, encouraging banks to work with affected customers while taking measures to keep money flowing smoothly between financial institutions.

headline.main: Fed Moves to Keep Credit Flowing and Money Markets Calm Amid Coronavirus Turmoil
headline.print_headline: Fed Encourages Institutions to Keep Credit Flowing Amid Turmoil
